description.text:
This adapter will mount a point and shoot compact camera to the eye piece tube of a microscope. It is designed for a tube 33mm (1.31”) diameter by 60mm (2.30”) long. With the eye piece installed, it will just slip over the tube. Screws on the side can be used to adjust for smaller tubes. A ¼ -20x3/4” screw is used to hold the camera to the adapter. The holes on the side can be tapped for 10-32 or ¼-20 screws. The PLA plastic was soft enough that it was possible to just drive the screws without tapping holes first .
Compared to a phone camera, the compact camera may give higher resolution and more control over zoom and exposure. The cameras come in various sizes so the adapter is slotted to allow sideways adjustment. It may be necessary to put a washer under the camera to adjust the height. The camera must be zoomed in until the image fills the screen.
The sample was printed on an Ultimaker original, 30% fill, with support, runtime 6 hours, material cost $2.50.

The part we have from Stratasys is apparantly printed with 0.2mm wide extrude and 0.1mm layers. There is obvious banding under a microscope between the side-by-side extrudate leaving tiny gaps inbetween every other pass. Suggests to me a aliasing issue in the printer.
It's the version without U under lid and with the two holes. It is not watertight and you can feel air escaping when blowing into it.
Another thing I see in the microscope is a rifled appearance of the finished surface. This appears to be result from previous layer being a support-layer that has later been removed. The finish in the dimples is smooth so it has probably not been ripped apart, but dissolved. Maby they print these in bulk using both the width and heigh capability of the machine to print a big block of them, then dissolve to seperate?

The book Bridge to Terabithia by Katherine Paterson is a popular children's book that is often read in Middle School literature classes. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridge_to_Terabithia_(novel) Imagination is a major theme in the book. In this project children are asked to build a bridge to the land of Terabithia and explain their design. Students were allowed to build their bridges out of any material (imagination!) including design a bridge that could be 3d printed.

• Give the students the assignment:
    “Every person has a story to tell; especially Jess. When Jess meets Leslie his world turned upside down. With the swing of one rope, Terabithia is born and the “real” becomes magic.
    • Creating a Bridge: Use your imagination! Imagine you had to create a bridge to get to Terabithia. What would it look like? What materials would you use? Actually make a bridge. You may use any materials you like, but remember make it imaginative! Also, add a paragraph (typed) on why you chose the design and materials you chose. Grammar and spelling will be graded.

description.text:
This is another attempt to upgrade on the cheap the QU-BD. In this, a remix of my first attempt http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1101105 and/or adaptation of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1058861 and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:177256 to use most of the electronics and hardware from the QU-BD 1/2Up. The extra hardware are some nuts and bolts #6 from my local hardware store, and an anUbis or E3D v6 Bowden, this keeps the inversion to minimum and you don't need to order online any other M2, 3, 4 or 5 screws, which are very hard and expensive. The rest of the parts can be printed in the QU-BD. All the files have been coded by me from scratch in OpenScad using the original images as reference. Eventually I'll post everything so anyone can use the files as they want. ----------------------------- PART LIST ----------------------------- 1) from any local hardware store (~$2):
  • machine screws round head #6-32 3/4" and 1"
  • machine screw nuts #6-32 regular and coarse
    2) from ebay or any other similar (~$11):
  • 1 x piece (450mm or so) of PFTE Teflon Filament Tubing ($1)
  • 1 x Pneumatic Coupling Coupler Fitting ($1)
  • 4 x bearings 608zz (~$3)
  • 3pcs Endstop Mechanical Limit Switch W/ LED and wire (~$5)
  • Nylon Plastic Zip Trim Wrap ($1)
    3) Filament for printed parts (i used PLA, layer 2.00 with 30% infill, maybe after ) (~$6)
    4) 99% of the original QU-BD 2Up hardware, and only 2 part of the chassis: the top bed and the filament-spool holder base.
    • ----------------------- TEST AND UPDATES ---------------------- 1) All parts printed with minor issues, not support needed.
    2) First try, to see how to put everything together and check weaknesses in the design: 1rst Test: https://youtu.be/DG5nCwstxoA
    3) 2nd Test: https://youtu.be/zQsfm_l_3WI (01/14/16) - check the belts
    4) 3rd Test: https://youtu.be/fliewcvI1NI (01/14/16) - test the End-Stops
    The y_base_end, x_axis_end, printer_head, and printer_head_support are fixed. The rest looks fine, for now.
    The x and y axis endstop are working great, but the z axis endstop has to be added to the design, for now it is attached with glue.
    5) 1rst Running Test: SUCCESS!!! It's Alive!!!
    I know that I have to do some fixes here and there but in general overall is working great, you can see the videos here:
    https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLp69TlCBx-zILPCqnHWXA330q658VN0Fz 6) This baby is running like a chram, I got 165mm x 165mm x 160mm. It's amazing the quality, and I'm getting more than 90% of success in the prints. ------------------------- UPDATES ---------------------------- 12/28/15 - Fixed: (1) z_motor_base, (2) x_motor_base. Added: (1) printer_head_support, (2) test_base, (3) base_short, (4) z_top_bowden_extruder_base.

title: "Creature / Monster" Project
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This "Monster" is built in Sculptris. Print this model to enjoy, or get inspired to create and print your own "Creature"!
This project is previewed as "beginner lessons" and experienced by classes with children form 9 to 12 years. 
Read on to understand the object and the structure of the project.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2-0.1mm

Infill:

10-15%

Notes: Probably you have to scale the object by 25.4 to convert it from inches to mm. Then you can scale it to the size you desire (e.g. 50%).

In this section I'll tell you about how I designed the 3D model of the Monster. In the next section I'll suggest an outline for a classroom project where students create their own creatures. The 3D model of this Monster was made from a single shere in sculptris. Sculptris is free, runs on Mac, Windows or Linux, and is really easy to learn. They offer even an understandable documentation. First I created the main forms with the "grab-tool". To add the details I used most of the "sculpt-tools". To finish I just had to save it and export it as *.obj-file. Attention:
  • Save your design from time to time.
  • Use Ctrl+Z go one step back.
  • Use "smooth" and "reduce" alternately to remove mistakes faster.
  • Go from the general to the particular. That makes your sculpting much faster.

Objectives
  • Create and design 3D printed creatures out of a ball-shere.
  • Learn basic 3D design skills and how to use sculptris as sculpting software.
  • Build complex designs on a computer by linking/comparing clay modelling and sculpting in CAD.
  • Explore geometrie, history, arts or math (depending on classroom usage).
    • Audiences
  • Anyone of any age that is new to 3D modeling/sculpting can use this modeling project to get started with sculptris.
  • This project is successfully experienced by four classes with children form 9 to 12 years during a project week.
    • Preparation
  • You need modelling clay, modelling tools and probably some coverage for the first part of the project.
  • Then Students will need access to computers with the software sulptris installed.
  • Sculptris is easier to use with a mouse than with a tablet or trackpad, so computer mice are recommended.
  • No previous 3D design experience is required for the students, even no familiarity with sculptris is needed.
  • The instructor should be comfortable answering modeling questions about sculptris and be able to advise students to avoid design features that might cause printing difficulties (overhangs, delicate features, etc).
  • You'll need a projector to make the instructions.
  • Give a reduced documentation to the students. This enables them to check or look up individually - helps you and your students.
  • Use some USB-Sticks to save the students work. It's easy and fast to use and you got all files bundled and mobile.
  • You'll need one or more 3D printers and some useful tools like pliers, files, sandpaper, etc.
  • And some acrylic paint to color the models with the students.

Introduction
Launch the project by a small fairy tail, fable or myth (cultural matrix). Or let the children write their own stories (language) to activate their creativity.
Then they should try to mold their own monster or protagonist out of modelling clay.
(Duration: 45-90') Clay-model made by student and an other one.. Introduction to Sculptris
Make a step-by-step introduction to sculptris using the projector. Show the basic navigation and the most important sculpting and saving tools. Try to make it as short as possible and as slowly as needed that everybody can follow you (imitate it).
(Duration: 20' or if necessairy 2 x 20') Exercise
Give the students time to try out, play, gamble and discover the functions and possibilities of the software. Allow discussions between the students. That way lots of problems will be solved in peers and it will create a motivated and positive ambience in the classroom.
(Duration: 45-90') Practice
Finally the students should try to recreate the "clay-monster" or a variant form of in CAD. Stay sensitive: Every student should be able to work with its capabilities. The positive experience is in this case more important then to reach the goal (perfect replica)!
(Duration: 45-90') Finish
Print the creatures and if you want you can color them with acrylic paint. 3D printed model (PLA white) and then colored Results At the end of this project, each student should have:
  • An initial clay-model of its creature
  • A CAD-model and -file in sculptris
  • A *.stl-file to print the object
  • A 3D printed creature

Review models, iterate
Compare the creatures in class or groups. Discuss what works or not, what's interesting, what could be made better. Start an interation-process.
This could go quite far, like how about adding movable parts? Geometry
How could we sculpt more precise?
Introduce front-, side- and top view. Make sketches or photos of your clay-model in these views. Import them to sculptris and restart a more precise sculpting. Front- and side view of the Projects
Create a board game, card game (quartet) or play environment to use these or further creatures to play in/with.
Rebuild a historical scene or a famous myth.
Make a stop-motion video using these or further creatures. Etc.

Well, the basic idea behind this project is to motivate children to get in touch with the game changing tools. That's why I decided to chose a subject of their world and interests. This artistic approach is moreover very open minded. That allows children to learn their own way, to work on its current level and to get still a positive experience in the end. (Well it's impossible to create wrong (or ugly) monsters?!)
The introducing with modelling clay builds a hand-on learning. It gives place to develope creativity and to experience the space/three-dimensionality. And even during the sculpting process it allows a check back and a crossover between the "analogous" and the digital world. This enables reflection and rich connections between reality and abstraction. Let this project be a jumping-off point for intrinsic motivated design activities of your students! And please stop to "design for learning" or spreading "learning objects". 3D printing is a powerful and creative learning tool but only if it is in the hands of the learner!

Removing support required care, and the empty triangles added no practical functions, so I made a remix using solid triangles. The new files are-

This is a muffin splitter aka muffin fork, intended to create nooks and crannies. I was practicing an "English" muffin recipe, baked a whole lot of muffins, and wanted something to split them properly. Searched for commercial examples. Tried a couple of ideas. This wedge was the simplest to make and worked the best. Just push it into the edge of a (thawed) muffin. Crumbs easily brush off. If used with care there should be no need to wash it. On an Afinia, using default settings, the print was near 60 minutes and used about 30 grams ABS. I chose this flat print orientation to minimize print time and support, to ease the removal of support, and I think the tips are least likely to break off when layers are oriented flat. YMMV. Scaling seems perfectly possible. I sized this to split 3 1/2 inch muffins for the Hamilton Beach Breakfast Sandwich Maker. A Metric file is provided.

The Robo-Prosthetic Development Kit was a design put together for the "Dimension 3D Printing Extreme Redesign Contest." It is a wire driven assembly designed for experiments in prosthetic control. I was lucky enough to be awarded the first prize scholarship for my submission and have since dedicated those resources towards the development of the Bioraptor multi-tool 3D printer. At the moment the Solidworks files are not ready for presentation, however the raw step files are not so bad and will hopefully provide a bit of inspiration to other with similar goals. If you have questions or comments please feel free to drop me a line, just remember as a full time student it might take me a bit of time to respond.
Thanks for your interest and best of luck,
Dale

New Museum Challenge Info:
I suppose on the most basic level this design is a (crude) derivative of my own hand as I spent more than a few minutes staring at it and wiggling fingers while sketching the models up. The primary improvements are that this hand is designed to make it easier to integrate electronic feedback mechanisms into the prosthetic. There are open screw holes everywhere to allow for small circuit boards and sensors to be mounted so that in addition to movement, the user would gain some sense of sensory input. While the initial requirements of the design required it to be made without embedded electronics or a specific recipient in mind, it's hard to imagine the this design being made in the time I took without a 3D printer. The final models seen in the pictures are actually scaled up versions of the original parts. Without having my colleges 3D printer to run several iterations and find the optimal work scale the models would have had to have been machined and in all likelihood, time constraints would have required me to just make one and hope that it came out perfectly the first time. I would also like to mention that, in an effort to support my college's efforts to obtain grants for a FABLab in Worcester, MA, should I win, I will be donating the Makerbot to that future lab the day it's doors open. I plan, in the intervening time, to use the Makerbot to complete my square yard print area "Bioraptor." If you have any questions about that effort please contact Carol King via Quinsigamond Community College at (508) 854-7526.

It is recommended that each part of the assembly be printer separately so that they may be oriented for optimal part strength.  All components were modeled and tested for snap fit tolerance using a Dimension 3D printer so printing a single joint set as a test is recommended if you are working with a different system.

In 1975 I constructed a wire model, an alpha carbon trace, of carp muscle calcium binding protein using<a href="http://www.umass.edu/microbio/rasmol/history.htm#bender"> Byron's bender</a>. A Thing-O-Matic, I thought, would allow me to build the same model much more easily. I began with a program from the University of Illinois, <a href="http://www.ks.uiuc.edu/Research/vmd/">VMD</a>, which displays protein structures in various ways and outputs STL files. While I was successful in making models with VMD's "tube" representation I was not able to print the alpha carbon "trace" representation. Then I found openSCAD. All one has to do is provide openSCAD with properly oriented spheres and cylinders and let it work its magic. It produces nice alpha traces that are very similar to a wire model. As well the openSCAD file provided can be easily modified to construct ball and stick models from the orthogonal coordinates of small molecules.

Input files are obtained from the Protein Data Bank and are identified by a 4 letter code, 5CPV for carp muscle calcium binding protein. Makescad.f is a fortran program that outputs calls to an openSCAD module. Insert the output file into makealpha.scad and execute it. On my machine makealpha.scad took two hours to render and the resulting scaled up STL file a bit over 4 hours to print. Carefully cutting the model from the support material took another hour. The result was the alpha carbon trace of carp muscle calcium binding protein pictured at the above left. Smaller proteins are easier to do. Two provided STL files are a neurotoxin from the green mamba, 1FAS, and the iron binding protein, rubredoxin, 5RXN. The neurotoxin is shown at the left of the bottom image and the iron binding protein on the right. The N-termini of the proteins are marked in blue and the C-termini in red. Thousands of sequences are available at the Protein Data Bank and if a smoother model pleases you it is not difficult to clean up the "tube" representation provided by VMD. Note that the current installer for GNU Fortran is very easy to use. Installation requires two mouse clicks. A single command entered at a command prompt compiles the source and produces an executable (gfortran makescad.f -o makescad.exe) A second command with the PDB file available makes the scad calls.
(makescad.exe &lt5CPV.pdb &gt5CPV.out) Byron's bender www.umass.edu/microbio/rasmol/history.htm#bender

description.text:
These distance holders for ACO ShowerDrain S solve for me three problems that i have with the original ones:
  • the original ones are too small and dont fit well (assuming the correct ones had been shipped).
  • it is too hard to remove the metal bar with fingers only - so one of the distance holders has a handle that is pushed down on one side, so that the other end of the handle rises and can be grabbed with the fingers.
  • an additional grid at those distance blocks helps to keep hair from clogging the main center grid too quickly.
    • final note: I have also added the 123d files so that in case the height needs to be adjusted, its fairly easy with 123d to use the push/pull feature.

description.text: A spiral vase and a cup with similar shape. The smaller piece was made as a test piece before printing out the bigger vase. It looks nice next to the vase so I added it. I used a grey vase (printed with PLA) already one week filled with water and flowers and it survived. The foto shows the first print after one week usage. Print with the setting spiral vase with only a single continous layer. The blue vase has still some small holes in the bottom layers that are to be tightened. So printing and examining the bottom layer well is important. The small cup is nice and usefull for tuning the print settings. I added an example for a transport case also printed with PLA in 3D (Print massive, NOT with the spiral vase setting :-) ). This case provides a secure shelter for the vase. The inside parts of the cover are to be carefully filed so that it fits securely on the case. I do not regard this case to be beautiful, but it did his job successfully. If you like this design, you may also check http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1063929 (I found this later after scanning all vases in thingiverse for similar vases).

Notes: I generated the gcode using slic3r with the option to print a spiral vase with 0.1 mm sheet height. I printed them in PLA with 120% filament flow to have a thicker and water proof wall.

Both vases are designed in Mathematica and exported as stl files from Mathematica.
The bottom part goes straight up, This helped me in printing all layers even the lowermost in a good quality.
